<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: REAL ESTATE; 
</P>
<P>
LORAL CORP. PLANS TO CONTINUE RENTING FORD AEROSPACE SITE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Michael Flagg Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By 1996, Loral Corp. will be paying $1-million-a-month rent for the 99-acre 
property where Ford Aerospace Corp.'s Newport Beach defense plant is located 
under a sublease with Ford. 
</P>
<P>
That rent might be stiff enough to inspire Loral, a New York-based defense 
contractor that is buying Ford Aerospace, to move the plant. 
</P>
<P>
Ford has been leasing the land on a long-term lease since 1958 at what were 
thought to be very low rates. 
</P>
<P>
Loral will start out paying $92,000 a month through mid-1995 for the site, 
according to the sublease. 
</P>
<P>
The rent then jumps to $550,000 per month and goes up to $1 million from 1996 
through 1998, when the sublease expires. 
</P>
<P>
The land, which belongs to the Irvine Co., could probably be profitably 
developed as a residential neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
But Loral officials say the company will stay in Newport Beach for at least the 
eight years of the sublease. 
</P>
<P>
"We'll stay on as long as we can and look for an appropriate solution at the 
end of the eight years," Loral Chairman Bernard Schwartz said recently. "The 
people out here are going to have to solve that problem. We in New York are not 
going to solve that problem." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
LORAL CORP; FORD AEROSPACE &amp; COMMUNICATIONS CORP; LEASES; LAND USE; IRVINE 
CO; NEWPORT BEACH (CA) -- DEVELOPMENT AND REDEVELOPMENT 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA090490-0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 271234 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 4, 1990, Tuesday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
