<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION; 
</P>
<P>
SOLAR PILOT SKIPS KITTY HAWK LEG 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
KITTY HAWK, N.C. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The pilot of the first aircraft to cross the country using sunshine for power 
today called off his attempt to complete the last 8 miles of the trip to an 
airstrip near the Wright Brothers Memorial. 
</P>
<P>
Northeast winds in excess of 20 m.p.h. forced Eric Raymond to cancel plans to 
fly the remaining miles from a turf farm, where he landed on Monday, to the 
First Flight Airport adjacent to the memorial. 
</P>
<P>
After announcing his plans, Raymond and his wife, Aida, went windsurfing. 
</P>
<P>
"It's really windy. The weather forecast is to be this way tomorrow. He made it 
to the coast," said Nancy McWilliams of Kitty Hawk Kites, which has been the 
headquarters for the final portion of the trip. "Tomorrow, he'll set up the 
plane for anybody who wants to see it and then head home to California." 
</P>
<P>
Eric Raymond first took off July 16 from Desert Center, Calif., about 200 miles 
east of Los Angeles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
