<P>
WORLD; 
</P>
<P>
MONGOL PRESIDENT VOWS REFORMS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, Mongolia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Punsalmaagiyn Ochirbat, dressed as an ancient Mongol warrior, drank a 
ceremonial bowl of fermented mare's milk and pledged swift free-market reforms 
during his inauguration as Mongolia's president today. 
</P>
<P>
Ochirbat, a Communist Party member who was reelected as president Monday, knelt 
before Parliament and kissed a national flag held by four soldiers with drawn 
swords before swearing himself in to Mongolia's most powerful post. 
</P>
<P>
Then he downed the bowl of mare's milk, a traditional drink in a nation where 
horses are revered as part of the legend of 13th-Century conqueror Genghis 
Khan. 
</P>
<P>
"We must swiftly start a transition period to a market economy," Ochirbat told 
delegates to the upper house of Parliament in an inaugural speech broadcast on 
television throughout the vast country. 
</P>
<P>
Ochirbat also stressed the importance of building economic ties with the Soviet 
Union, China and other nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
